--- PDF SUMMARY (Document was 91 pages long) ---
The document was too long to read directly, so here is a detailed summary of all sections:

The working draft paper by Frank Kachanoff and colleagues explores two distinct types of psychological threats posed by COVID-19: realistic threats (to physical or financial safety) and symbolic threats (to sociocultural identity). The authors developed and validated a 10-item COVID-19 threat scale across three studies involving 1,195 participants.

Key methodologies include principal component analysis for assessing factor structure, confirmatory factor analysis, and invariance analysis for validation of the scale. Convergent validity was assessed by examining associations with individual differences related to threat sensitivity, such as need for cognitive closure and beliefs in a dangerous world.

The studies found that both types of threats predict higher anxiety and lower well-being, but they have different impacts on public health behavior. Realistic threat significantly predicts greater compliance with public health measures (e.g., social distancing), whereas symbolic threat predicts lower compliance with these measures. Furthermore, symbolic threat often leads to creative ways to maintain social identity, such as through virtual interactions.

The findings suggest that understanding these psychological threats can inform strategies to improve public health initiatives and compliance, highlighting the utility of social psychological theory in pandemics. The research is ongoing and subject to further refinement based on community feedback.

In this study, 399 American participants were initially recruited from MTurk in March 2020, with 346 completing all measures during the COVID-19 crisis. Of these, 193 participants had also completed measures pre-COVID-19 in October 2019. The research focused on the development and validation of the Integrated COVID-19 Threat Scale, designed to measure perceived realistic and symbolic t
